Single Cell Genomics Analysis Tutorial (Seurat)

Abstract¶

  A "Cell type" is a category used to identify cells that share morphological or phenotypic characteristics. The precise number of distinct cell types is not defined, but as of 2021, Cell Ontology lists over 2,300 different cell types.
(Osumi-Sutherland D, Xu C, Keays M et al, 2021)
Due to the diverse nature of different cell types, analyzing cells based on their types can have significant potential. However, even since the introduction of NGS (Next-Generation Sequencing), there have been challenges in conducting such analyses for a while. Over time, thanks to technological advancements, we have now entered an era where we can profile the expression levels of thousands of genes within a single cell. From this technology, we can identify the composition of cells within tissues obtained from experiments or surgeries, understand the specific characteristics of each cell in various situations, and potentially uncover previously unknown cell types.

 The scRNA-seq method includes the process of extracting and interpreting the barcodes (cell barcodes) and Unique Molecular Identifiers (UMIs) from the sequencing reads, and followed by these steps :

  • Count matrix generation (method-specific steps): This involves preparing sequencing reads, separating samples, aligning reads to a reference genome, and quantifying gene expression levels for each cell.

  • Quality assessment of raw counts: Removing low-quality cells to ensure the reliability of data used in subsequent analyses.

  • Clustering of filtered counts: Grouping cells into clusters based on similarities in their transcriptional profiles, with each cluster representing distinct cell types or states.

  • Downstream analysis: These may include additional analyses like differential gene expression studies, trajectory inference, data visualization, and interpretation based on research objectives.

These steps are crucial for analyzing single-cell RNA sequencing data, providing insights into the cellular composition and gene expression patterns within a given sample or tissue.

 For these single-cell genomics analysis, there are tools like Cell-Ranger , Scanpy and Seurat.
Cell-Ranger is a set of analysis pipelines that process Chromium single cell data to align reads, generate feature-barcode matrices, perform clustering and other secondary analysis. Scanpy is a Python-based scalable toolkit for analyzing single-cell gene expression data built jointly with anndata. And Seurat is a toolkit based on the R that provides various functionalities for single-cell genomics analysis.

  Among these tools, We will start with count data obtained from tools like CellRanger and then introduce a tutorial on Single Cell Genomics Analysis using Seurat. For this tutorial, we utilize a dataset of Peripheral Blood Mononuclear Cells (PBMC) freely available from 10X Genomics (download web page).

 This tutorial serves as a prerequisite for preparing the input files required for Tenet GRN analysis and continues at Preparing Tenet input files using Monocle2 Pseudotime

1. Setup¶

Return to Index

Before diving into the analysis, preparing the environment is followed by loading libraries in R and importing the downloaded data(your data).

To use Seurat in R, you'll need to install the Seurat library. Find the 'Seurat' package and install it. You can typically do this through the package manager in your R interface or by running a specific install command.
Simply, install.packages('Seurat') (Installation)

In [1]:
# load the libraries
library(dplyr)

2. Preprocessing¶

Return to Index

 The following steps outline the typical pre-processing procedure for scRNA-seq data in Seurat. These steps involve selecting and filtering cells based on quality control measurements, normalizing and scaling the data, and identifying highly variable features.

2-1. Filtering the cells¶


  • percent.mt: a percentage of cell reads originating from the mitochondrial genes
    • Low-quality / dying cells often exhibit extensive mitochondrial contamination
    • We calculate mitochondrial QC metrics with the PercentageFeatureSet() function, which calculates the percentage of counts originating from a set of features
In [3]:
pbmc_seurat_object[["percent.mt"]] <- PercentageFeatureSet(pbmc_seurat_object, pattern = "^MT-")
NOTE: The pattern provided ("^MT-") works for human gene names
  • nCount_RNA: number of UMI counts (transcripts) per cell

  • nFeature_RNA: number of genes detected per cell.

    • Low-quality cells or empty droplets will often have very few genes
    • Cell doublets or multiplets may exhibit an aberrantly high gene count Similarly, the total number of molecules detected within a cell (correlates strongly with unique genes)

  • number of genes detected per UMI: the complexity of our dataset (more genes detected per UMI, more complex our data)

In [4]:
pbmc_seurat_object$log10GenesPerUMI <- log10(pbmc_seurat_object$nFeature_RNA) / log10(pbmc_seurat_object$nCount_RNA)
In [5]:

#  The filtering criteria applied to this dataset are as follows.(adjust to your dataset)
pbmc_seurat_object <- subset(pbmc_seurat_object, 
               subset = (nFeature_RNA > 200 & nFeature_RNA < 2500) &
               (nCount_RNA > 500) &
               (log10GenesPerUMI > 0.80)&
               (percent.mt < 5)
              )

2-2. Normalizing the data¶


Count normalization is crucial for ensuring accurate comparisons of gene expression between cells (or samples).

  • Sequencing depth: Accounting for sequencing depth is essential when comparing gene expression between cells.

  • Gene length: Considering gene length is essential when comparing expression levels among different genes within the same cell. Without this consideration, it may seem like the number of reads mapped to a longer gene has the same count/expression as a shorter gene that is actually more highly expressed.

In [8]:
# Normalized values will be stored in pbmc_seurat_object[["RNA"]]@data.
pbmc_seurat_object <- NormalizeData(pbmc_seurat_object)

2-3. Identifying highly variable features¶


Next, we determine a subset of features that display significant cell-to-cell variation in the dataset, meaning they are highly expressed in some cells while having low expression in others. This approach, employed by us and others, enhances the ability to identify biological signals in single-cell datasets.

In [9]:
pbmc_seurat_object <- FindVariableFeatures(pbmc_seurat_object, selection.method = "vst", nfeatures = 2000)

# Identify the 10 most highly variable genes
top10_variable_genes <- head(VariableFeatures(pbmc_seurat_object), 10)

options(repr.plot.width=8, repr.plot.height=8)  
LabelPoints(plot = VariableFeaturePlot(pbmc_seurat_object), points = top10_variable_genes, repel = TRUE)

When using repel, set xnudge and ynudge to 0 for optimal results

Warning message:
“Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous x-axis”

2-4. Scaling the data¶


we perform a linear transformation, commonly referred to as 'scaling,' which is a standard pre-processing step before applying dimension reduction techniques such as PCA.
The ScaleData() function accomplishes the following:

  • It shifts the expression of each gene so that the mean expression across cells becomes 0.
  • It scales the expression of each gene so that the variance across cells becomes 1.
In [10]:
# Scaled Value will be stored in pbmc_seurat_object[["RNA"]]@scale.data
all.genes <- rownames(pbmc_seurat_object)
pbmc_seurat_object <- ScaleData(pbmc_seurat_object, features = all.genes)

Centering and scaling data matrix



3. Dimension Reduction and Clustering¶

Return to Index

Next, we conduct Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on the scaled data. By default, the input comprises the features that were previously identified as variable, but you can specify a different subset using the "features" argument if desired.

3-1. Principal Component Analysis (PCA)¶


Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a technique used to emphasize variation as well as similarity, and to bring out strong patterns in a dataset (dimensionality reduction).

In [11]:
pbmc_seurat_object <- RunPCA(pbmc_seurat_object, features = VariableFeatures(object = pbmc_seurat_object))

The elbow plot is helpful when determining how many PCs we need to capture the majority of the variation in the data. The elbow plot visualizes the standard deviation of each PC. Where the elbow appears is usually the threshold for identifying the majority of the variation.

In [12]:
ElbowPlot(object = pbmc_seurat_object, 
          ndims = 50)

In this instance, we notice a distinct 'elbow' pattern emerging around PC9-10, indicating that the majority of the genuine signal is encompassed within the initial 10 principal components (PCs).

**Cell cycle scoring**
 Restricting the variation from uninteresting sources of variation (sequencing depth, cell cycle differences, mitochondrial expression, batch effects, etc.) are important to keep the major sources of variation.
Once the data is normalized for sequencing depth, we can assign each cell a score, based on its expression of G2/M and S phase markers. After scoring the cells for cell cycle, we would like to determine whether cell cycle is a major source of variation in our dataset using PCA

s.genes <- cc.genes$s.genes
g2m.genes <- cc.genes$g2m.genes
pbmc_seurat_object <- CellCycleScoring(pbmc_seurat_object,
                                       s.features = s.genes, 
                                       g2m.features = g2m.genes)

# the CellCycleScoring result will be stored at pbmc_seurat_object[["Phase"]]

DimPlot(pbmc_seurat_object,
        reduction = "pca",
        group.by= "Phase",
        split.by = "Phase")

We can use PCA visualization to check the extent of the cell cycle's influence on the data and make a decision on whether to regress out remove its effects.

pbmc_seurat_object <- ScaleData(pbmc_seurat_object, vars.to.regress = c("S.Score", "G2M.Score"), features = rownames(pbmc_seurat_object))



3-2. Clustering¶


 Seurat uses a graph-based clustering approach, which embeds cells in a graph structure, using a K-nearest neighbor (KNN) graph (by default), with edges drawn between cells with similar gene expression patterns. Then, it attempts to partition this graph into highly interconnected ‘quasi-cliques’ or ‘communities’

 We will utilize the FindClusters() function to conduct graph-based clustering. The "resolution" parameter plays a crucial role in determining the level of detail in the resulting clusters and should be fine-tuned for each specific experiment. For datasets containing 3,000 to 5,000 cells, setting the resolution in the range of 0.4 to 1.4 typically produces satisfactory clustering results. Higher resolution values result in more clusters, which can be beneficial for larger datasets.

 The FindClusters() function allows us to input multiple resolutions and automatically assess the clustering granularity, saving us the effort of running the function separately for each resolution to find the most suitable one.

In [13]:
pbmc_seurat_object <- FindNeighbors(pbmc_seurat_object, dims = 1:10)
# Determine the clusters for various resolutions                                
pbmc_seurat_object <- FindClusters(object = pbmc_seurat_object,
                               resolution = c(0.5, 1.0, 1.2))

3-3. UMAP visualization¶


 To visualize the cell clusters, there are a few different dimensionality reduction techniques that can be helpful. The most popular methods include t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding(t-SNE) and Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection(UMAP) techniques

 Both methods aim to group cells with similar local neighborhoods in high-dimensional space together in low-dimensional space. To use these methods, you need to specify the number of PCA dimensions to use for visualization, and it's recommended to use the same number of PCs as input for the clustering analysis. In this case, we will proceed with the UMAP method for visualizing the clusters.

In [15]:
# If you haven't installed UMAP, you can do so via reticulate::py_install(packages =
# 'umap-learn')
pbmc_seurat_object <- RunUMAP(pbmc_seurat_object, dims = 1:10)

4. Annotation and Differentially Expressed Genes Analysis¶

Return to Index

 Annotation involves assigning cell types to clusters based on their distinct characteristics, typically using markers and other relevant information. Seurat can help you find markers that define clusters via differential expression.

4-1. Exploring known cell type markers¶


 Now that the cells are clustered, we can explore their cell type identities by examining known markers. For example if we were interested in exploring known immune cell markers

4-2. DEG analysis¶


FindAllMarkers() compares each cluster against all other clusters to identify potential marker genes.
This function has three important arguments that serve as thresholds for determining whether a gene is considered a marker:

  • logfc.threshold: This is the minimum log2 fold change for the average expression of a gene in the cluster relative to the average expression in all other clusters combined. The default threshold is 0.25.

  • min.diff.pct: This sets the minimum percentage difference between the percentage of cells expressing the gene in the cluster and the percentage of cells expressing the gene in all other clusters combined.

  • min.pct: This argument ensures that only genes detected in a minimum fraction of cells in either of the two populations are tested. It's meant to speed up the function by not testing genes that are very infrequently expressed. The default threshold is 0.1.

In [19]:
# Depending on dataset, this command can quite take long to run
pbmc_seurat_object.markers <- FindAllMarkers(pbmc_seurat_object, only.pos = TRUE, min.pct = 0.25, logfc.threshold = 0.25)
pbmc_seurat_object.markers %>%
    group_by(cluster) %>%
    top_n(n = 5, wt = avg_log2FC) -> top5

4-3. Assigning cell type identity to clusters(Annotation)¶


Lastly, we can assign cell types to each cluster based on cell type markers and differentially expressed genes (DEG).

In [21]:
clusters <- pbmc_seurat_object$RNA_snn_res.0.5
cluster_names <- rep("Unknown", length(clusters))


cluster_names[clusters %in% c(3)] <- "B"
cluster_names[clusters %in% c(6)] <- "NK"
# cluster_names[clusters %in% c(0, 2, 4)] <- "T"
cluster_names[clusters %in% c( 4)] <- "CD8+ T"
# cluster_names[clusters %in% c(0,2)] <- "CD4+ T"
cluster_names[clusters %in% c(0)] <- "CD4+ T"
cluster_names[clusters %in% c(2)] <- "Memory CD4+ T"
cluster_names[clusters %in% c(1)] <- "CD14+ Mono"
cluster_names[clusters %in% c(7)] <- "cDC"   
cluster_names[clusters %in% c(5)] <- "FCGR3A+ Mono"
